8. The Orozz'er and Riny.

The erozier and ring are mentioned in the Canens of the fourth Council of Toledo (c. 27) and in the De Ecclesiasticis Officiis (IL, 5) of St. Isidore as insignia of the episcopal office. They must, therefore, have been in use in Spain as early as the beginning of the seventh century. In the elevent-h century they were almost universally used, as is shown by the history of the strife concerning investiture. Indeed, long before this date, some of the lives of the saints drawn up in countries conforming to the Gallican rite, give us ground for belief that the use of them was not peculiar to Spain. Further support of this belief is found in the employment of the crozier, under the name of cambuta, in the dedica- tion rites according to the Gallican Ohurch. At Rome, on the other hand, this sign of office was unknown. When the episcopal crozier‚ with its very natural symbolism, had been everywhere adopted, it was a cause of surprise that the Pope, the shepherd of the shepherds, was the only one not to make habitual use of the pastoral staff.
